snippet.textDisplay:
Just because you don't know the person you're condemning doesn't mean that you're being objective. You're just allowing yourself to not empathise.



The solution is to do exactly what you don't want to do - to ask yourself "what if this was me/someone i care about?". Would it be okay to lock you or someone you care about up for the rest of their life for no reason other than to keep 100 prisoners locked up who may or may not go to commit more crimes in the future? Prisoners who may or may not be falsely convicted too? The obvious answer to that is no. You can't start locking up innocent people or the system collapses. That's why Blackstone's ratio exists in the first place. Locking someone up for a crime they didn't commit is an injury, just as sure as any other crime. If you do that then you're no better than the people you want to lock up. Not to mention that one day it's gonna come back to bite you in the ass when it's your turn to be locked up for a crime you didn't commit "for the greater good".


As for the trolley problem, that's not really related to the prisoner problem. The trolley problem demands that not killing the one person results in the certain deaths of many others. Releasing 100 prisoners from prison does not neccessarily mean that other people will suffer. It COULD mean that other people suffer, but it could also just as well not and you don't know which. That's the difference.
